<HEADLINE>
<P>
RECALCITRANT BATHER MEETS A SOAPY FATE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By United Press International 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NAIROBI, Kenya 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
enyan man who did not bathe for three years met a soapy fate when an 
exasperated mob pursued him through the streets, peeled off his clothes and 
forcibly washed him in public, the semiofficial Kenya Times newspaper reported 
today. 
</P>
<P>
The man, whose name was withheld, was set upon by odor-sensitive colleagues 
after he repeatedly declined invitations to break his 36-month ablutionary 
fast, the newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
Fellow artisans in Othaya, 60 miles north of Nairobi, chased the pungent 
offender through the streets, held him down and scrubbed him with soap and a 
rough piece of gunnysack. The sacking helped remove the accumulated layers of 
filth, the paper explained. 
</P>
<P>
The man's clothes were burned, and he was given a new set after friends held a 
collection for him. 
</P>
<P>
The crowd also force-marched the man to a barber shop, where the victim had his 
hair cut and his beard trimmed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
